      • createKeyAsync

        public Future<KeyBundle> createKeyAsync(String vault,
                                        String keyName,
                                        String keyType,
                                        Integer keySize,
                                        String[] keyOps,
                                        KeyAttributes keyAttributes,
                                        Map<String,String> tags)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Creates a new key and returns its attributes.

        This method actually creates a new key version for the informed key name. Existing key versions for that name are left untouched and don't cause a conflict exception.

        The new key will become the current version for the informed key name, and will be used whenever the key version is not explicitly informed on an operation.

        Specified by:
        createKeyAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        keyName - The key name.
        keyType - The key type identifier. You may use a constant from JsonWebKeyType.
        keySize - The key size, which corresponds to the key strength. If null, a default size is used for the specified type.
        keyOps - The operations that will be allowed on the new key. You may use values from JsonWebKeyOperation.
        keyAttributes - An optional instance of KeyAttributes. If null, default values are used.
        tags - An optional map of tags. If null, the key will have no tags.
        Returns:
        A key bundle containing data about the created key.

      • getKeysAsync

        public Future<ListKeysResponseMessage> getKeysAsync(String vault,
                                                    Integer maxresults)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Returns a list of keys in the vault. This method returns only one entry for each key in the vault (i.e. if a key has multiple versions, it's returned only once).

        The service may use paging. In order to obtain all keys, the caller must verify the value of ListKeysResponseMessage.getNextLink(), and if not null, call KeyVaultClient.getKeysNextAsync(String) to return the next page.

        The caller is not required to fetch all pages (i.e. the server does not hold significant resources). However, the link to next page may expire, so make sure you use it as soon as possible.

        Specified by:
        getKeysAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        maxresults - The maximum number of keys to return. If null, all keys are returned. This has no influence over the number of pages.
        Returns:

      • getKeyVersionsAsync

        public Future<ListKeysResponseMessage> getKeyVersionsAsync(String vault,
                                                           String keyName,
                                                           Integer maxresults)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Returns a list of versions of a vault key.

        The service may use paging. In order to obtain all versions, the caller must verify the value of ListKeysResponseMessage.getNextLink(), and if not null, call KeyVaultClient.getKeysNextAsync(String) to return the next page.

        The caller is not required to fetch all pages (i.e. the server does not hold significant resources). However, the link to next page may expire, so make sure you use it as soon as possible.

        Specified by:
        getKeyVersionsAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        keyName - The name of key to get versions from.
        maxresults - The maximum number of keys to return. If null, all versions are returned. This has no influence over the number of pages.

      • importKeyAsync

        public Future<KeyBundle> importKeyAsync(String vault,
                                        String keyName,
                                        KeyBundle keyBundle,
                                        Boolean importToHardware)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Imports an existing key into the service.

        This method actually creates a new key version for the informed key name. Existing key versions for that name are left untouched and don't cause a conflict exception.

        The key being imported will become the current version for the informed key name, and will be used whenever the key version is not explicitly informed on an operation.

        Specified by:
        importKeyAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        keyName - The name of key to import.
        keyBundle - Key material and attributes. The key identifier must not be informed.
        importToHardware - true if the key is to be imported to hardware, false if not. If null, the system will use the default for key type.
        Returns:
        A key bundle containing data about the imported key.

      • backupKeyAsync

        public Future<byte[]> backupKeyAsync(String vault,
                                     String keyName)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Creates a backup of a key. The backup can be used to restore the key into the same vault, or into other vaults of same subscription.

        All versions of the informed key are backed up. The backup value opaquely identifies the key name and version, as well as the current version.

        IMPORTANT: The service does not store the backup value anywhere. The caller must properly save the backup value in order to restore it afterwards.

        Specified by:
        backupKeyAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        keyName - The name of key to backup.
        Returns:
        An opaque byte[] containing the key backup. The data is encrypted to a high-security key and cannot be inspected. It can only used by a restore operation.
        See Also:
        KeyVaultClient.restoreKeyAsync(String, byte[])

      • restoreKeyAsync

        public Future<KeyBundle> restoreKeyAsync(String vault,
                                         byte[] keyBundleBackup)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Restores a key into the specified vault.

        All versions of the backed up key are restored. The key name is obtained from the backup value. The current version becomes the one that was current when the backup value was obtained.

        Specified by:
        restoreKeyAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        keyBundleBackup - The key backup value, typically obtained through KeyVaultClient.backupKeyAsync(String, String).
        Returns:
        A key bundle containing data about the restored key. While this operation restores all key versions, only the current version of key is returned.

      • getSecretsAsync

        public Future<ListSecretsResponseMessage> getSecretsAsync(String vault,
                                                          Integer maxresults)
        Description copied from interface: KeyVaultClient
        Returns a list of secrets in the vault. This method returns only one entry for each secret in the vault (i.e. if a secret has multiple versions, it's returned only once).

        The service may use paging. In order to obtain all secrets, the caller must verify the value of ListSecretsResponseMessage.getNextLink() , and if not null, call KeyVaultClient.getSecretsNextAsync(String) to return the next page.

        The caller is not required to fetch all pages (i.e. the server does not hold significant resources). However, the link to next page may expire, so make sure you use it as soon as possible.

        Specified by:
        getSecretsAsync in interface KeyVaultClient
        Parameters:
        vault - The vault URI.
        maxresults - The maximum number of secrets to return. If null, all secrets are returned. This has no influence over the number of pages.
        Returns:
